      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so if i have a circuit with a resistor and an inductor in series, how do i actually calculate the total impedance? do i just add the resistance and the reactance together like a normal addition problem?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No, you cannot simply add resistance and reactance like a regular sum because they are out of phase with each other. When calculating the total impedance ($\\text{Z}$) in a series $\\text{RL}$ circuit, you must use the Pythagorean theorem. The formula is $\\text{Z} = \\sqrt{\\text{R}^2 + \\text{X}_{\\text{L}}^2}$, where $\\text{X}_{\\text{L}}$ is the inductive reactance. This squaring and square-rooting accounts for the $90$-degree phase difference between the resistance and the inductor.",
      "source": "target",
