      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, it is absolutely common, especially in high-frequency circuits or when using specialized components, for reactance to dominate resistance. When $\\text{X}_{\\text{L}}$ is much larger than $\\text{R}$, the circuit behaves almost purely inductively, and the impedance ($\\text{Z}$) will be very close to $\\text{X}_{\\text{L}}$. In such cases, the phase angle approaches $90$ degrees, meaning the current lags the voltage significantly, which is the essence of the phase shift you mentioned.",
